l min-w-0 flex-col agent-turn" tabindex="-1"><div class="flex max-w-full flex-col grow"><div data-message-author-role="assistant" data-message-id="71bff814-c450-4476-b7c8-9bf01ee1edb7" dir="auto" class="min-h-8 text-message relative flex w-full flex-col items-end gap-2 text-start break-words whitespace-normal [.text-message+&amp;]:mt-1" data-message-model-slug="gpt-5-2"><div class="flex w-full flex-col gap-1 empty:hidden first:pt-[1px]"><div class="markdown prose dark:prose-invert w-full break-words dark markdown-new-styling"><p data-start="0" data-end="357">Excellent choice. Below is <strong data-start="27" data-end="51">a full LaTeX section</strong>, written to sit <em data-start="68" data-end="76">before</em> Section D, that explicitly engages <em data-start="112" data-end="201"><em data-start="113" data-end="187">Lacanian psychoanalytic interpretations as articulated in Helen Rollins’</em> Psychocinema</em>**—while keeping the argument rigorous, non-derivative, and clearly positioning Spherepop as a <strong data-start="296" data-end="356">formal alternative rather than a metaphorical rephrasing</strong>.</p>
<p data-start="359" data-end="453">This section is careful to respect psychoanalytic theory without collapsing Spherepop into it.</p>
