<p data-start="295" data-end="376">I group citations by <em data-start="316" data-end="326">function</em>, not just by name, to make the structure legible.</p>
<hr data-start="378" data-end="381">
<h2 data-start="383" data-end="406">Abstract &amp; Framing</h2>
<p data-start="407" data-end="466"><strong data-start="407" data-end="466">(Event-history, irreversibility, meaning-as-commitment)</strong></p>
<ul data-start="468" data-end="669">
<li data-start="468" data-end="500">
<p data-start="470" data-end="500">Heidegger — <em data-start="482" data-end="498">Being and Time</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="501" data-end="538">
<p data-start="503" data-end="538">Whitehead — <em data-start="515" data-end="536">Process and Reality</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="539" data-end="616">
<p data-start="541" data-end="616">Landauer — <em data-start="552" data-end="614">Irreversibility and Heat Generation in the Computing Process</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="617" data-end="669">
<p data-start="619" data-end="669">Bennett — <em data-start="629" data-end="667">Logical Reversibility of Computation</em></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="671" data-end="866"><strong data-start="671" data-end="679">Why:</strong><br data-start="679" data-end="682">
The move from state to history, and from representation to commitment, rests on Heideggerian temporality and process metaphysics, with physical irreversibility as the technical anchor.</p>
<hr data-start="868" data-end="871">
<h2 data-start="873" data-end="918">Section 1 — <em data-start="888" data-end="918">The Axiom of Irreversibility</em></h2>
<ul data-start="920" data-end="1070">
<li data-start="920" data-end="952">
<p data-start="922" data-end="952">Heidegger — <em data-start="934" data-end="950">Being and Time</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="953" data-end="1005">
<p data-start="955" data-end="1005">Heidegger — <em data-start="967" data-end="1003">The Question Concerning Technology</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="1006" data-end="1025">
<p data-start="1008" data-end="1025">Landauer (1961)</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1026" data-end="1070">
<p data-start="1028" data-end="1070">Ashby — <em data-start="1036" data-end="1068">An Introduction to Cybernetics</em></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="1072" data-end="1127"><strong data-start="1072" data-end="1080">Why:</strong><br data-start="1080" data-end="1083">
Irreversibility is framed simultaneously as:</p>
<ul data-start="1128" data-end="1266">
<li data-start="1128" data-end="1166">
<p data-start="1130" data-end="1166">existential (thrownness, facticity),</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1167" data-end="1208">
<p data-start="1169" data-end="1208">technological (enframing vs revealing),</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1209" data-end="1230">
<p data-start="1211" data-end="1230">physical (entropy),</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1231" data-end="1266">
<p data-start="1233" data-end="1266">and cybernetic (loss of variety).</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="1268" data-end="1271">
<h2 data-start="1273" data-end="1314">Section 2 — <em data-start="1288" data-end="1314">The Morphology of Choice</em></h2>
<ul data-start="1316" data-end="1420">
<li data-start="1316" data-end="1345">
<p data-start="1318" data-end="1345">Aristotle — <em data-start="1330" data-end="1343">Metaphysics</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="1346" data-end="1373">
<p data-start="1348" data-end="1373">Girard — <em data-start="1357" data-end="1371">Linear Logic</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="1374" data-end="1420">
<p data-start="1376" data-end="1420">Pierce — <em data-start="1385" data-end="1418">Types and Programming Languages</em></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="1422" data-end="1498"><strong data-start="1422" data-end="1430">Why:</strong><br data-start="1430" data-end="1433">
The distinction between pop, bind, refuse, and collapse draws on:</p>
<ul data-start="1499" data-end="1640">
<li data-start="1499" data-end="1540">
<p data-start="1501" data-end="1540">Aristotelian actuality vs potentiality,</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1541" data-end="1579">
<p data-start="1543" data-end="1579">linear logic’s resource sensitivity,</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1580" data-end="1640">
<p data-start="1582" data-end="1640">and type-theoretic discipline around irreversible effects.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="1642" data-end="1645">
<h2 data-start="1647" data-end="1691">Section 3 — <em data-start="1662" data-end="1691">The Mechanics of Commitment</em></h2>
<ul data-start="1693" data-end="1818">
<li data-start="1693" data-end="1737">
<p data-start="1695" data-end="1737">Jacobson — <em data-start="1706" data-end="1735">Thermodynamics of Spacetime</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="1738" data-end="1779">
<p data-start="1740" data-end="1779">Verlinde — <em data-start="1751" data-end="1777">On the Origin of Gravity</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="1780" data-end="1799">
<p data-start="1782" data-end="1799">Landauer (1961)</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1800" data-end="1818">
<p data-start="1802" data-end="1818">Bennett (1973)</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="1820" data-end="1888"><strong data-start="1820" data-end="1828">Why:</strong><br data-start="1828" data-end="1831">
The Lagrangian/Hamiltonian formalism is not metaphorical:</p>
<ul data-start="1889" data-end="2005">
<li data-start="1889" data-end="1938">
<p data-start="1891" data-end="1938">commitment is treated as an intensive quantity,</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1939" data-end="1974">
<p data-start="1941" data-end="1974">freedom as a consumable resource,</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1975" data-end="2005">
<p data-start="1977" data-end="2005">collapse as renormalization.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="2007" data-end="2101">This section implicitly relies on the <em data-start="2045" data-end="2090">thermodynamic reinterpretation of structure</em> tradition.</p>
<hr data-start="2103" data-end="2106">
<h2 data-start="2108" data-end="2157">Section 4 — <em data-start="2123" data-end="2157">Renormalization through Collapse</em></h2>
<ul data-start="2159" data-end="2296">
<li data-start="2159" data-end="2185">
<p data-start="2161" data-end="2185">Grothendieck — <em data-start="2176" data-end="2183">SGA 1</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="2186" data-end="2243">
<p data-start="2188" data-end="2243">Mac Lane &amp; Moerdijk — <em data-start="2210" data-end="2241">Sheaves in Geometry and Logic</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="2244" data-end="2296">
<p data-start="2246" data-end="2296">Bennett — <em data-start="2256" data-end="2294">Logical Reversibility of Computation</em></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="2298" data-end="2430"><strong data-start="2298" data-end="2306">Why:</strong><br data-start="2306" data-end="2309">
Collapse is formally a quotient and categorically universal.<br data-start="2369" data-end="2372">
The analogy to renormalization and compression depends on:</p>
<ul data-start="2431" data-end="2513">
<li data-start="2431" data-end="2456">
<p data-start="2433" data-end="2456">quotient constructions,</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2457" data-end="2482">
<p data-start="2459" data-end="2482">kernel/image reasoning,</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2483" data-end="2513">
<p data-start="2485" data-end="2513">and logical irreversibility.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="2515" data-end="2518">
<h2 data-start="2520" data-end="2587">Section 5 — <em data-start="2535" data-end="2587">Psychocinema and the Limits of Retroactive Meaning</em></h2>
<ul data-start="2589" data-end="2726">
<li data-start="2589" data-end="2650">
<p data-start="2591" data-end="2650">Lacan — <em data-start="2599" data-end="2648">The Four Fundamental Concepts of Psychoanalysis</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="2651" data-end="2691">
<p data-start="2653" data-end="2691">Deleuze — <em data-start="2663" data-end="2689">Cinema 2: The Time-Image</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="2692" data-end="2726">
<p data-start="2694" data-end="2726">Helen Rollins — <em data-start="2710" data-end="2724">Psychocinema</em></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="2728" data-end="2773"><strong data-start="2728" data-end="2736">Why:</strong><br data-start="2736" data-end="2739">
This section explicitly contrasts:</p>
<ul data-start="2774" data-end="2842">
<li data-start="2774" data-end="2802">
<p data-start="2776" data-end="2802">retroactive signification,</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2803" data-end="2820">
<p data-start="2805" data-end="2820">cinematic time,</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2821" data-end="2842">
<p data-start="2823" data-end="2842">and symbolic lack</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="2844" data-end="2901">with Spherepop’s <strong data-start="2861" data-end="2900">forward-only, non-revisable history</strong>.</p>
<p data-start="2903" data-end="2965">Rollins is essential here as the contemporary synthesis point.</p>
<hr data-start="2967" data-end="2970">
<h2 data-start="2972" data-end="3019">Section 6 — <em data-start="2987" data-end="3019">From Calculus to Visualization</em></h2>
<ul data-start="3021" data-end="3131">
<li data-start="3021" data-end="3068">
<p data-start="3023" data-end="3068">Tristan Needham — <em data-start="3041" data-end="3066">Visual Complex Analysis</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="3069" data-end="3131">
<p data-start="3071" data-end="3131">Tristan Needham — <em data-start="3089" data-end="3129">Visual Differential Geometry and Forms</em></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="3133" data-end="3235"><strong data-start="3133" data-end="3141">Why:</strong><br data-start="3141" data-end="3144">
Your insistence that nested bubbles/spheres are <strong data-start="3192" data-end="3224">structural, not illustrative</strong> relies on:</p>
<ul data-start="3236" data-end="3367">
<li data-start="3236" data-end="3282">
<p data-start="3238" data-end="3282">Needham’s legitimacy of geometric intuition,</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3283" data-end="3316">
<p data-start="3285" data-end="3316">topology-over-metric reasoning,</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3317" data-end="3367">
<p data-start="3319" data-end="3367">and spatial reasoning without diagrams-as-proof.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="3369" data-end="3424">This section would read as unjustified without Needham.</p>
<hr data-start="3426" data-end="3429">
<h2 data-start="3431" data-end="3487">Section D — <em data-start="3446" data-end="3487">Cognitive Agents as Log-Bound Processes</em></h2>
<ul data-start="3489" data-end="3615">
<li data-start="3489" data-end="3508">
