<p data-start="3511" data-end="3534">Rosen — <em data-start="3519" data-end="3532">Life Itself</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="3535" data-end="3576">
<p data-start="3537" data-end="3576">Friston — <em data-start="3547" data-end="3574">The Free-Energy Principle</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="3577" data-end="3615">
<p data-start="3579" data-end="3615">Dennett — <em data-start="3589" data-end="3613">The Intentional Stance</em></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="3617" data-end="3664"><strong data-start="3617" data-end="3625">Why:</strong><br data-start="3625" data-end="3628">
This section redefines cognition as:</p>
<ul data-start="3665" data-end="3854">
<li data-start="3665" data-end="3699">
<p data-start="3667" data-end="3699">constraint accumulation (Rosen),</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3700" data-end="3766">
<p data-start="3702" data-end="3766">model construction without representational transparency (Marr),</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3767" data-end="3802">
<p data-start="3769" data-end="3802">irreversible inference (Friston),</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3803" data-end="3854">
<p data-start="3805" data-end="3854">and agent-relative worldhood (Dennett, inverted).</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="3856" data-end="3859">
<h2 data-start="3861" data-end="3913">Section E — <em data-start="3876" data-end="3913">The Agent as Endofunctor and Parser</em></h2>
<ul data-start="3915" data-end="4098">
<li data-start="3915" data-end="3957">
<p data-start="3917" data-end="3957">Lawvere — <em data-start="3927" data-end="3955">Adjointness in Foundations</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="3958" data-end="4015">
<p data-start="3960" data-end="4015">Mac Lane — <em data-start="3971" data-end="4013">Categories for the Working Mathematician</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="4016" data-end="4046">
<p data-start="4018" data-end="4046">Awodey — <em data-start="4027" data-end="4044">Category Theory</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="4047" data-end="4098">
<p data-start="4049" data-end="4098">Erik Meijer — <em data-start="4063" data-end="4096">Category Theory for Programmers</em></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="4100" data-end="4173"><strong data-start="4100" data-end="4108">Why:</strong><br data-start="4108" data-end="4111">
The endofunctor framing and parser reinterpretation depend on:</p>
<ul data-start="4174" data-end="4305">
<li data-start="4174" data-end="4205">
<p data-start="4176" data-end="4205">categorical compositionality,</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4206" data-end="4228">
<p data-start="4208" data-end="4228">functorial identity,</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4229" data-end="4305">
<p data-start="4231" data-end="4305">and Meijer’s work connecting category theory to computation without state.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="4307" data-end="4310">
<h2 data-start="4312" data-end="4373">Section F — <em data-start="4327" data-end="4373">Sheaf-Theoretic Interpretations of Worldhood</em></h2>
<ul data-start="4375" data-end="4459">
<li data-start="4375" data-end="4401">
<p data-start="4377" data-end="4401">Grothendieck — <em data-start="4392" data-end="4399">SGA 1</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="4402" data-end="4459">
<p data-start="4404" data-end="4459">Mac Lane &amp; Moerdijk — <em data-start="4426" data-end="4457">Sheaves in Geometry and Logic</em></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="4461" data-end="4521"><strong data-start="4461" data-end="4469">Why:</strong><br data-start="4469" data-end="4472">
This section would collapse without sheaf theory:</p>
<ul data-start="4522" data-end="4600">
<li data-start="4522" data-end="4546">
<p data-start="4524" data-end="4546">locality vs globality,</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4547" data-end="4570">
<p data-start="4549" data-end="4570">gluing as commitment,</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4571" data-end="4600">
<p data-start="4573" data-end="4600">collapse as sheafification.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="4602" data-end="4655">It is mathematically orthodox but semantically novel.</p>
<hr data-start="4657" data-end="4660">
<h2 data-start="4662" data-end="4701">Conclusion — <em data-start="4678" data-end="4701">Joy in a Finite World</em></h2>
<ul data-start="4703" data-end="4818">
<li data-start="4703" data-end="4735">
<p data-start="4705" data-end="4735">Heidegger — <em data-start="4717" data-end="4733">Being and Time</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="4736" data-end="4773">
<p data-start="4738" data-end="4773">Whitehead — <em data-start="4750" data-end="4771">Process and Reality</em></p>
</li>
<li data-start="4774" data-end="4818">
<p data-start="4776" data-end="4818">Ashby — <em data-start="4784" data-end="4816">An Introduction to Cybernetics</em></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="4820" data-end="4858"><strong data-start="4820" data-end="4828">Why:</strong><br data-start="4828" data-end="4831">
The conclusion synthesizes:</p>
<ul data-start="4859" data-end="4942">
<li data-start="4859" data-end="4881">
<p data-start="4861" data-end="4881">finitude as meaning,</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4882" data-end="4905">
<p data-start="4884" data-end="4905">commitment as relief,</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4906" data-end="4942">
<p data-start="4908" data-end="4942">and worldhood as lived constraint.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="4944" data-end="4989">This is where the philosophical weight lands.</p>
